WEBVTT

00:02.561 --> 00:05.245
♪<i> It seems today</i>
<i> that all you see</i> ♪

00:05.397 --> 00:08.081
♪<i> Is violence in movies</i>
<i> and sex on TV</i> ♪

00:08.217 --> 00:11.844
♪<i> But where are those</i>
<i> good old-fashioned values</i> ♪

00:11.995 --> 00:14.847
♪<i> On which we used to rely?</i> ♪

00:14.998 --> 00:18.242
♪<i> Lucky there's a family guy</i> ♪

00:18.260 --> 00:21.503
♪<i> Lucky there's a man</i>
<i> who positively can do</i> ♪

00:21.522 --> 00:23.080
♪<i> All the things that make us</i> ♪

00:23.098 --> 00:24.506
♪<i> Laugh and cry</i> ♪

00:24.525 --> 00:30.237
♪<i> He's... a...</i>
<i> Fam... ily... Guy!</i> ♪

00:36.095 --> 00:37.611
Ah, the record store--

00:37.763 --> 00:39.596
full of the greatest albums
of all time

00:39.615 --> 00:42.041
and the employees
who hate every one of 'em.

00:42.192 --> 00:43.950
Hey, do you have
the Eagles'<i> Greatest Hits?</i>

00:44.045 --> 00:46.545
Yeah. It's under "O"
for "obvious."

00:46.696 --> 00:47.938
And "overrated."

00:47.956 --> 00:49.773
Thank you, bearded failures.

00:49.866 --> 00:51.383
You know, it's stores like this
where you learn

00:51.493 --> 00:53.535
about the real history
of rock and roll,

00:53.554 --> 00:55.888
not the watered-down version
you get in every movie

00:56.039 --> 00:57.297
about a musician's life.

00:57.391 --> 00:59.374
Yeah, all those biopics
are the same story:

00:59.468 --> 01:01.510
unsupportive parents, hit song,

01:01.620 --> 01:02.561
band turmoil...

01:02.788 --> 01:04.788
Having giant horse teeth
and dying of AIDS.

01:04.807 --> 01:06.548
All of 'em are exactly the same.

01:06.567 --> 01:08.625
Check out this section
for the Doors.

01:08.718 --> 01:10.127
Jim Morrison is a legend,

01:10.220 --> 01:11.144
whether we like it or not.

01:11.297 --> 01:12.571
He had the good sense to die

01:12.798 --> 01:15.223
before we could see him
at the Pechanga Casino and go,

01:15.317 --> 01:17.225
"Oh, my God, that's him?"

01:17.244 --> 01:19.578
♪

01:19.729 --> 01:21.080
<i> It was the '60s,</i>

01:21.231 --> 01:24.324
<i> a time of great</i>
<i>fateful missed Frisbee catches.</i>

01:24.476 --> 01:26.643
<i> The iconic band</i>
<i> was formed one day</i>

01:26.662 --> 01:29.646
<i> when Ray Manzarek met</i>
<i> Jim Morrison on Venice Beach.</i>

01:29.665 --> 01:32.316
Thanks! I'm Ray Manzarek.
What's your name?

01:32.334 --> 01:34.075
Jim Morrison. Light my fire.

01:34.095 --> 01:35.577
W-Wait a minute, wait.
What'd you just say?

01:35.596 --> 01:36.411
Say that again.

01:36.505 --> 01:37.262
Light my fire?

01:37.414 --> 01:39.098
Yeah, that! That could be a song

01:39.249 --> 01:41.100
that's tolerated
for generations!

01:41.251 --> 01:43.102
What do you say
you and I form a band?

01:43.329 --> 01:45.178
A band? But this is the '60s.

01:45.331 --> 01:48.273
We don't have nearly enough
floppy heads of hair to do that.

01:48.500 --> 01:50.851
Hey, you guys starting a band?
Mind if we join?

01:50.945 --> 01:52.093
Yes. You're both in.

01:52.187 --> 01:54.004
We are gonna be huge, you guys.

01:54.022 --> 01:55.614
And nothing's
gonna get between us--

01:55.765 --> 01:57.449
not drugs or alcohol

01:57.601 --> 02:00.344
or the first toxic relationship
that comes my way.

02:00.362 --> 02:04.105
Look out! Easily manipulated
runaway comin' through!

02:04.125 --> 02:06.125
Screw you guys!
I'm following that lady,

02:06.276 --> 02:08.018
and there's nothing
you can do about it!

02:08.111 --> 02:09.294
I<i> am</i> the Doors!

02:09.521 --> 02:10.537
Jim, be reasonable.

02:10.689 --> 02:12.856
We haven't even named ourselves
that yet.

02:12.875 --> 02:14.133
Look, I'm gonna get right to it

02:14.284 --> 02:17.970
and say I miss making music
with you bastards.

02:18.121 --> 02:19.138
Thanks!

02:19.247 --> 02:21.047
I'm Charles Manson.
What's your name?

02:21.200 --> 02:22.790
Jim Morrison. Kill Sharon Tate.

02:22.810 --> 02:24.810
Wait a minute.
What did you just say?

02:24.961 --> 02:26.478
Say that again.

02:26.705 --> 02:28.630
-♪
-(humming)

02:28.649 --> 02:32.709
♪<i> This is how women</i>
<i> on drugs dance.</i> ♪

02:32.802 --> 02:33.986
Yeah.

02:36.157 --> 02:37.656
Jim Morrison.
Love me two times.

02:37.883 --> 02:39.491
W-Wait a minute.
What'd you just say?

02:39.643 --> 02:40.909
Say that again.

02:42.163 --> 02:44.496
Well, Jim, I'm flattered
you broke into my home,

02:44.648 --> 02:47.557
but I have a serious boyfriend
and I think you should leave.

02:47.576 --> 02:48.742
But I'm a rock star!

02:48.894 --> 02:50.485
And he's an astronaut.

02:50.504 --> 02:53.172
You know, unfortunately for you,
this is the one time in history

02:53.323 --> 02:55.823
where astronauts are cooler
than rock stars.

02:55.843 --> 02:57.492
Well, I don't care.
You're my muse,

02:57.511 --> 03:01.180
and I'm moving in with
my trash bags of bad poetry.

03:02.999 --> 03:04.016
"The caterpillar--

03:04.167 --> 03:05.926
"a tiny hair snake?

03:06.078 --> 03:09.579
Nay. Because of his many,
many legs."

03:09.598 --> 03:10.689
"The snake.

03:10.840 --> 03:13.192
"A large, hairless caterpillar?

03:13.419 --> 03:16.253
Nay. On account of no legs."

03:16.271 --> 03:17.921
"The snakeapillar..."

03:17.940 --> 03:20.257
Wow. Such a genius, huh?

03:20.350 --> 03:22.259
Now, I do have a boyfriend,

03:22.352 --> 03:24.277
but I'm also a free spirit.

03:24.430 --> 03:28.281
(quietly): That's my fun
little way of sayin' I'm a slut.

03:28.434 --> 03:31.877
So, how'd you like to have sex
with my kite-sized woman weave?

03:32.028 --> 03:36.715
Mm, it'll mesh perfectly with
my giant nest of tight ringlets.

03:36.866 --> 03:38.625
(moaning)

03:38.777 --> 03:40.126
LOIS:
Oh, Jim.

03:40.279 --> 03:42.036
PETER:
Call me the Lizard King.

03:42.056 --> 03:44.539
LOIS:
(moans) Oh, Lizard King!

03:44.633 --> 03:47.059
PETER:
Yeah. Now call me
Archduke Salamander,

03:47.286 --> 03:48.227
Emperor of Newts.

03:48.378 --> 03:49.895
LOIS:
(exhales) You're the Archduke...

03:50.122 --> 03:50.878
PETER:
Ah, I'm done.

03:50.898 --> 03:52.789
(Velcro ripping)

03:52.808 --> 03:54.958
